graph-element" class=3D"text-gray-800 my-rem16px text-rem19px leading-rem34=
px  ">Your report may provide blood alcohol level test results in different=
 ways depending on the laboratory that processes the test. The results are =
typically reported in the percentage of blood alcohol content (BAC) =E2=80=
=94 for example, 0.03% BAC. They can also be listed as grams per milliliter=
 (g/mL). This test result would be 0.03 g/100 mL.</p><p data-identity=3D"pa=
ragraph-element" class=3D"text-gray-800 my-rem16px text-rem19px leading-rem=
34px  ">The results may also indicate =E2=80=9Cpositive=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=
=9Cnegative,=E2=80=9D meaning you did have alcohol in your blood or you had=
 no alcohol in your blood, respectively.</p><p data-identity=3D"paragraph-e=
lement" class=3D"text-gray-800 my-rem16px text-rem19px leading-rem34px  ">T=
he timing of a BAC test can affect the accuracy of the results. A blood alc=
ohol test is only accurate within six to 12 hours after your last alcohol-c=
ontaining drink. If you have questions or concerns about your results, talk=
 to your healthcare provider and/or a lawyer, depending on your situation.<=
/p></div></div></div><div><div data-identity=3D"article-section" id=3D"addi=
